{
  "text": "Akt has been shown to inhibit JNK1 activity by binding to JIP1 [CITATION_1] . JIP1 assembles the Mixed Lineage Kinase 3 (MLK3), MKK7 and JNK1 in a complex which can be disrupted by Akt binding. In this study, Akt expression in rapamycin-untreated samples is stable (Figure 4c) , and pre-treatment with rapamycin activates Akt (Figure 4d ). Akt phosphorylation was increased at serine 473 ~1.48-fold after TNF-\u03b1 stimulation (Figure 4d ). The increase of serine 473 phosphorylation is due to the action of TNF-\u03b1 (Tsou et al. 2010) . Conversely, JNK1 is also deactivated (Figure 3b ). In contrast, there was no detection of p-Akt in rapamycin-untreated samples (Figure 4d ), strengthening the case that only phosphorylated Akt inhibit JNK1 signalling by binding to JIP1 and disrupting the formation of the MKK7-JNK1 scaffold. This contradicts observations from [CITATION_2] , in which co-expression of wild-type or kinase-dead Akt reduced formation of a JIP1-mediated ternary complex between MLK3 and JNK1. However, the same authors [CITATION_3] conceded that JIP1 phosphorylates Akt at serine 473. Other researchers have also established indirect links to Akt-JIP1 binding [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] . Taken together, these experiments demonstrate that p-Akt binding to JIP1 inhibits JIP1's ability to assemble active JNK signalling complexes. Presumably, rapamycin treatment will positively affect the binding affinity of Akt towards JIP1 by activating it at its serine 473 residue.",
  "correct_citation": {
    "[CITATION_1]": "13933000",
    "[CITATION_2]": "13933000",
    "[CITATION_3]": "13933000",
